into a decline and died, leaving him to mourn her in his verse. The Anglicized form of the name is sometimes taken to be from the feminine of Latin <i>unus</i> ‘one’. It is the name used by Spenser for the lady of the Red Cross Knight in The Faerie Queene: he probably had Latin rather than Irish in mind, even though he worked in Ireland for a while. The Irish name has also been Anglicized as   Unity  ,   Juno  ,   Winifred  , and   Agnes ."],"variants":[{"name":"Euna","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Ùna ."]},{"name":"Oona","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Úna ."]},{"name":"Una","meanings":["Anglicized form of Irish Úna . In Irish legend Úna is the mother of the hero Conn Cétchathach (Conn of the Hundred Battles). It was also the name of the beloved of the 17th-century poet  Tomás Láidir Costello : banned by her parents from seeing him, Úna fell into a decline and died, leaving him to mourn her in his verse. The Anglicized form of the name is sometimes taken to be from the feminine of Latin <i>unus</i> ‘one’. It is the name used by Spenser for the lady of the Red Cross Knight in The Faerie Queene: he probably had Latin rather than Irish in mind, even though he worked in Ireland for a while. The Irish name has also been Anglicized as   Unity  ,   Juno  ,   Winifred  , and   Agnes ."]},{"name":"Oonagh","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Úna ."]},{"name":"Juno","meanings":["Anglicized form of the Irish name Úna , assimilated to the name of the Roman goddess <i>Juno</i>, consort of Jupiter."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Unk Magistri was born in 1180. He had at least 1 son with Mrs Magister."},"et":{"1180–":"1180–Surnud","1182–Female":"1182–Surnud","1205–Male":"1205–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1180–Male":"1180–Surnud","1205":"1205","Abt 1205":"umbes 1205","1182":"1182","1180":"1180","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"1180–":"1180–Kuollut","1182–Female":"1182–Kuollut","1205–Male":"1205–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1180–Male":"1180–Kuollut","1205":"1205","Abt 1205":"noin